# PART 6: LAYER 3 — ILP VALIDATOR

## 6.1 Simple English

> **ILP = Integer Linear Programming.** It's a mathematical method that finds the best solution that satisfies a set of hard rules. We use it to validate that the neural network's predictions make sense — like a fact-checker.

## 6.2 What Is Integer Linear Programming?

ILP solves problems like:
- Find values for variables x₁, x₂, ... ∈ {0, 1} (integers only)
- That maximise an objective function
- Subject to constraints

**Example:** "Given that the model predicted ORDER_ID='#abc', is this valid?"

Our constraints:
```
Constraint 1: ORDER_ID value must match regex \d{3,8}     (3-8 digit number)
Constraint 2: FLIGHT_ID must match [A-Z]{2}\d{2,4}        (airline code)
Constraint 3: No token can have two conflicting labels    (exclusivity)
Constraint 4: At most 1 ORDER_ID per sentence             (cardinality)
Constraint 5: If B-X is predicted, span text must be non-empty
```

## 6.3 Why OR-Tools CP-SAT?

**OR-Tools** is Google's open-source constraint solver — the same engine used for Google Maps routing, warehouse optimisation, and production scheduling. We use its **CP-SAT** (Constraint Programming - Satisfiability) mode.

**Performance:** Solves our NER constraints in **0.03 milliseconds** per message. This is essentially free computationally.

## 6.4 Example — ILP Rejecting a Bad Prediction

Suppose the model predicts `#abc` as `B-ORDER_ID`:

```
Constraint: ORDER_ID must match \d{3,8}
"#abc" → regex test fails
ILP: REJECT → set label to O
```

Result: "Failed ILP Constraints" — the entity is removed and the system knows to be cautious.

## 6.5 ILP as a Safety Net

Think of it this way:
- Neural network: "I'm 85% sure #abc is an ORDER_ID"
- ILP: "Order IDs are always numbers. #abc has letters. Rejected."

The ILP enforces **domain knowledge** that would take millions of training examples for a neural network to learn perfectly.

---

# PART 7: LAYER 4 — MC DROPOUT (UNCERTAINTY QUANTIFICATION)

## 7.1 Simple English

> The model runs **10 times** on the same message but with **different neurons randomly disabled** each time. If all 10 runs agree → the model is confident. If they give different answers → the model is uncertain → flag for human review.

## 7.2 Background: What Is Dropout?

During training, **Dropout** randomly zeros out 35% of neurons in each forward pass:
```
Normal:  [0.8, 1.2, -0.5, 0.3, 0.9] → Linear Layer → next layer
Dropout: [0.0, 1.2,  0.0, 0.3, 0.0] → Linear Layer → next layer (3 neurons zeroed)
```

**Why?** Forces the network to not rely on any single neuron — improves generalisation.

During inference (normal mode), Dropout is **turned OFF** — all neurons active.

## 7.3 Monte Carlo Dropout — The Trick

**MC Dropout** (Gal & Ghahramani, 2016): Keep Dropout **ON during inference** and run T=10 times. This approximates drawing from the **posterior distribution** over model weights — i.e., it estimates how confident the model is.

```
Pass 1:  ORDER_ID=5678 (conf 0.94), ISSUE_TYPE=return (conf 0.88)
Pass 2:  ORDER_ID=5678 (conf 0.97), ISSUE_TYPE=return (conf 0.91)
Pass 3:  ORDER_ID=5678 (conf 0.95), ISSUE_TYPE=return (conf 0.90)
...
Pass 10: ORDER_ID=5678 (conf 0.93), ISSUE_TYPE=return (conf 0.87)

Mean confidence ORDER_ID  = 0.95   → Very certain ✓
Mean confidence ISSUE_TYPE = 0.89  → Certain ✓
```

## 7.4 Entropy — Measuring Uncertainty Mathematically

**Information Entropy** (Shannon, 1948):
```
H(p) = -Σ p(x) × log₂(p(x))
```

- If model always says ORDER_ID with confidence 1.0 → H = 0 (perfectly certain)
- If model says ORDER_ID 50% of the time and something else 50% → H = 1 (maximum uncertainty)
- Our threshold: H > 0.5 nats → uncertain → human review

**Example for "hi I want to return order #5678 🙏":**
```
ORDER_ID  entropy H = 0.02   → certain (route: automated)
ISSUE_TYPE entropy H = 0.09  → certain (route: automated)
Overall H  = 0.05            → very low → FULL AUTOMATION
```

**Example for "idk my order #9999 or somewhere":**
```
ORDER_ID entropy H = 0.45    → uncertain (conflicting signals)
ISSUE_TYPE entropy H = 0.62  → very uncertain
Overall H = 0.54             → HIGH uncertainty → HUMAN REVIEW
```

## 7.5 Computational Cost

- Each MC Dropout pass ≈ 9ms on CPU
- T=10 passes ≈ 92ms total
- This is the main latency bottleneck (not the CRF or ILP)

Why T=10 and not T=100? Uncertainty estimate standard error ≈ σ/√T. Going from T=10 to T=100 cuts error by 3× but costs 10× more time. T=10 gives ±2% uncertainty estimate error — good enough for production.

---

# PART 8: LAYER 5 — DECISION ENGINE

## 8.1 Simple English

> Takes everything the model learned — extracted entities, confidence, emojis — and decides: **How urgent is this? What should we do? Who handles it?**

## 8.2 Urgency Classification — The 3-Tier System

**Tier 1: HIGH URGENCY (🔴)**  
Triggered by:
- Anger emojis: `😠 😡 🤬 💀 🔥 😤`
- Alert emojis: `⚠️ 🚨 🆘 ‼️`
- Keywords: "urgent", "asap", "emergency", "immediately", "not delivered", "third time"
- High MC entropy (model is uncertain — better safe than sorry)

Action: Immediate Zendesk priority ticket + Slack alert to support team

**Tier 2: MEDIUM URGENCY (🟡)**  
Triggered by:
- Sadness/frustration emojis: `😢 😭 💔 😞 😔`
- Sarcasm emojis: `😏 🙄 🤡`
- Model confidence below 0.75

Action: Zendesk ticket + human review queue

**Tier 3: LOW URGENCY (🟢)**  
Triggered by:
- Positive/polite emojis: `🙏 👍 ✅ 😊 ❤️`
- No anger signals
- Model confidence above 0.85

Action: Automated response sent — no human needed

## 8.3 Routing Decision Logic

```python
if urgency == "high":
    route → human_review
    dispatch → zendesk_priority + slack_alert

elif urgency == "medium" OR overall_entropy > 0.5:
    route → human_review
    dispatch → zendesk_normal

else:  # low urgency AND high confidence
    route → automated
    dispatch → postgresql_log (no ticket needed)
```

## 8.4 Why Emoji-Based Urgency?

Traditional methods use keyword matching: "angry" → urgent. But:
- `😠` is MORE informative than the word "angry" — emojis carry emotion more reliably
- They're harder to fake (customers who type 😡 are genuinely frustrated)
- Emojis cross language barriers — `😤` means the same in English, Spanish, Hindi

---

# PART 9: LAYER 6 — API DISPATCHER

## 9.1 Simple English

> Once we know what to do, this layer sends the data to the right external service — like a post office routing letters to the correct destination.

## 9.2 The Services and When They're Used

| Service | Library Used | Triggered When | What It Does |
|---------|-------------|----------------|--------------|
| **Zendesk** | `requests` (REST API) | Urgency: HIGH or MEDIUM | Creates a support ticket with customer's extracted data |
| **Slack** | `slack_sdk` | Urgency: HIGH | Posts to #urgent-support channel |
| **Twilio** | [twilio](file:///Users/itsyash/Desktop/desktop/coding/messi/api.py#171-184) | Urgency: HIGH | Sends SMS to on-call support agent |
| **Salesforce** | `simple_salesforce` | High-value customers | Updates CRM contact record |
| **Firebase** | `firebase_admin` | Always | Logs event for analytics dashboard |
| **PostgreSQL** | `psycopg2` | Always | Stores structured record in database |

## 9.3 Dry-Run Mode

All API calls run in **dry-run mode** by default — they log what they WOULD do but don't actually call the APIs. This is controlled by the `--live` flag.

Why? During development and demo, you don't want to create real Zendesk tickets for every test message.

```python
if self.dry_run:
    log_json("WOULD DISPATCH", payload)   # just log it
else:
    zendesk_client.create_ticket(payload)  # real API call
```

---

# PART 10: FULL WORKED EXAMPLE

## Processing "hi I want to return order #5678 🙏"

### Step 1 — Tokenisation
```
Input:  "hi I want to return order #5678 🙏"
Output: ["hi", "I", "want", "to", "return", "order", "#5678", "🙏"]
```
No emoji gluing issues here. Straightforward split.

### Step 2 — Embedding Each Token
```
"hi"     → spaCy[300d] + emoji[50d, all 0 — not emoji] + char["h","i"→64d]
"#5678"  → spaCy[~zero, unknown word] + emoji[50d, all 0] + char["#","5","6","7","8"→64d]
"🙏"    → spaCy[~zero, not English] + emoji[50d, learned polite vector] + char[emoji chars→64d]
```

### Step 3 — BiLSTM Forward Pass
```
Forward  →:
"hi" → h₁=[0.2,-0.1,...] (320d, learned "greeting context")
"want" → h₃=[0.5,0.3,...] (sees "hi" + "I" context)
"return" → h₅=[0.8,-0.2,...] (sees full left context — probably ISSUE_TYPE)
"#5678" → h₇=[0.9,0.1,...] (sees "return order" context — ORDER_ID pattern)

Backward ←:
"#5678" ← h₇'=[0.7,...] (sees "🙏" to the right — positive context)
"return" ← h₅'=[0.6,...] (sees "order #5678 🙏" to the right)
```

### Step 4 — Linear Layer + CRF
```
Emission scores for each token:
  "hi"     → O=9.2, B-ORDER_ID=0.1, B-ISSUE_TYPE=0.3, ...  → O wins
  "return" → O=2.1, B-ORDER_ID=0.5, B-ISSUE_TYPE=8.7, ...  → B-ISSUE_TYPE wins
  "#5678"  → O=1.2, B-ORDER_ID=9.4, B-ISSUE_TYPE=0.2, ...  → B-ORDER_ID wins
  "🙏"    → O=9.8, B-ORDER_ID=0.1, ...                     → O wins

After CRF Viterbi:
  ["O", "O", "O", "O", "B-ISSUE_TYPE", "O", "B-ORDER_ID", "O"]
```

### Step 5 — ILP Validation
```
B-ORDER_ID on "#5678":
  text = "5678" (after stripping #)
  matches regex \d{3,8}: YES ✓
  
B-ISSUE_TYPE on "return":
  "return" in issue_type allowlist: YES ✓
  
No overlapping spans: ✓
Max 1 ORDER_ID: ✓ (only #5678)

ILP RESULT: PASS ✓
```

### Step 6 — MC Dropout (T=10)
```
All 10 passes agree:
  ORDER_ID = "#5678"  confidence 96%  entropy H=0.02
  ISSUE_TYPE = "return"  confidence 91%  entropy H=0.09
  
Overall entropy = 0.05  →  LOW uncertainty → can automate safely
```

### Step 7 — Decision Engine
```
Emoji analysis: "🙏" → POSITIVE_POLITE category → base urgency = LOW
Keyword check: "return" → neutral (not "asap", not "damaged") → LOW
MC entropy: 0.05 < 0.5 → confidence HIGH → confirm LOW

Urgency:  🟢 LOW
Routing:  ✅ automated
Action:   send_return_form
```

### Step 8 — API Dispatch (dry-run)
```
PostgreSQL: INSERT INTO events {
  text: "hi I want to return order #5678 🙏",
  order_id: "5678",
  issue_type: "return",
  urgency: "low",
  routing: "automated",
  timestamp: 2026-03-02T13:00:00
}
[DRY RUN — not a real database call]
```

### Final Output to User
```json
{
  "record":    {"ORDER_ID": "#5678", "ISSUE_TYPE": "return"},
  "urgency":   "LOW",
  "routing":   "automated",
  "action":    "send_return_form",
  "latency":   137.4,
  "confidence": {"order_id": 0.96, "issue_type": 0.91}
}
```

**In simple English for the customer:**
> "Your return request for order #5678 has been received. We've sent you the return form automatically. Expect a response within 24 hours."

---

# PART 11: EVALUATION METRICS

## 11.1 F1 Score — The Main Metric

The F1 score is the **harmonic mean** of Precision and Recall:

```
Precision = TP / (TP + FP)
          = "Of all ORDER_IDs we predicted, how many were correct?"

Recall    = TP / (TP + FN)
          = "Of all real ORDER_IDs in the data, how many did we find?"

F1        = 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall)
```

**Why F1 and not just accuracy?** Tags are imbalanced — most tokens are O. If we predict O for everything, accuracy = 70% but F1 = 0.0. F1 penalises models that ignore rare entity tags.

**Macro F1:** Average F1 across ALL tag types equally (rare tags count as much as common ones).

## 11.2 Cohen's Kappa (κ)

Measures agreement between model predictions and gold labels, corrected for chance:
```
κ = (Observed Agreement - Chance Agreement) / (1 - Chance Agreement)
```
- κ = 1.0 → perfect agreement
- κ = 0.0 → no better than random
- κ = 0.54 (our result in benchmark) → moderate to good agreement

## 11.3 Span-Level F1

Token-level F1 rewards partial credit. Span-level F1 requires the FULL entity to be correct:
- "order #5678 damaged" → predicting "B-ORDER_ID, I-ORDER_ID" when gold is "B-ORDER_ID" → token-level credit but span-level FAIL

Span-level F1 is stricter and more meaningful for real-world use.

---

# PART 12: WHY MESSI AND NOT AN LLM?

| Factor | GPT-4 / Claude | MESSI |
|--------|---------------|-------|
| **Cost** | $0.005–$0.10 per message | $0.00 (runs locally) |
| **Latency** | 2–10 seconds | 140ms (< 0.14s) |
| **Privacy** | Data sent to third party | 100% on your hardware |
| **Explainability** | "The AI said so" | Every decision logged with reasons |
| **Consistency** | Varies (temperature = randomness) | Deterministic — same input always → same output |
| **Availability** | Breaks if OpenAI's API is down | Always available |
| **Auditability** | No audit trail | Full JSON log of every decision step |
| **Custom rules** | Must be in the prompt (unreliable) | Hard-coded in ILP (guaranteed) |

**When would you use an LLM instead?**  
- Open-ended questions that need creative reasoning
- Tasks with no fixed output format
- Low-volume, one-off tasks where latency doesn't matter

**MESSI is the right choice when:**
- You process thousands of messages per minute
- Rules must be guaranteed (compliance, legal)
- Data privacy is a requirement
- Latency must be under 200ms

