# QUICK REFERENCE: Q&A

**Q: Why BiLSTM and not a Transformer (BERT)?**  
A: BERT is 110M parameters and requires GPU. BiLSTM-CRF is 6.8M parameters, runs on CPU in 5ms. For a structured extraction task with a fixed tag set, BiLSTM-CRF gives 80-90% of BERT's performance at 5% of the compute cost.

**Q: Why did F1 jump to 0.80 previously, but is now around 0.56?**  
A: Our initial tests used synthetic, perfectly templated data ("flight [X] delayed"), making it easy for the neural network to score 80%+. We actively chose to replace this with 100% real-world, noisy data (tweets, banking logs). Dropping to 56% is mathematically expected when moving from clean synthetic data to noisy real data — but the 56% model is vastly superior because it can actually handle real human unpredictability.

**Q: Why do emojis matter for NLP?**  
A: Emojis carry emotion and intent that is NOT expressed in words. "order not delivered" is ambiguous. "order not delivered 😠" is HIGH urgency. "order not delivered 🙏" might be LOW urgency (polite inquiry). Emojis are linguistic signals that standard NLP tools discard.

**Q: What is the partition function Z in CRF?**  
A: Z is the sum of exp(score) over ALL possible tag sequences. It normalises the scores into a proper probability distribution. Computing it naively is exponentially expensive, so we use the Forward Algorithm (dynamic programming) to compute it in O(n×K²) — linear in sequence length.

**Q: Why not just use regex to extract ORDER_ID?**  
A: Regex can't understand context. `/\#\d+/` would match "#1234" in "my phone number is #1234" incorrectly. The BiLSTM understands that "#1234" is an ORDER_ID only when it follows "order" or similar context — regex cannot.

**Q: What is label smoothing?**  
A: Instead of training the model to predict probability 1.0 for the correct label and 0.0 for others, we train it to predict [(1-α)=0.92](file:///Users/itsyash/Desktop/desktop/coding/messi/demo.py#27-28) for the correct label and `α/K=0.08/11` for each other label. This prevents the model from being overconfident on noisy training data and improves generalisation.

